whether a `` relation '' of an object is one of its properties may complicate such an argument . 
according to bundle theory ,  an object consists of its properties and nothing more: thus neither can there be an object without properties nor can one even `` conceive '' of such an object; for example ,  bundle theory claims that thinking of an apple compels one also to think of its color ,  its shape ,  the fact that it is a kind of fruit ,  its cells ,  its taste ,  or at least one other of its properties . 
critics also question how any two given properties are determined to be properties of the same object if there is no `` substance '' in which they both `` inhere '' . 
consequently ,  the idea of a self must be eliminated . 
the inability to comprehend any aspect of the thing other than its properties implies ,  this argument maintains ,  that one cannot conceive of a `` bare particular ''  -lrb-  a `` substance '' without properties  -rrb-  ,  an implication that directly opposes substance theory . 
